President Barack Obama has announced his intent to nominate David T. Matsuda as Administrator of the Maritime Administration at the Department of Transportation. Matsuda has been serving as Deputy Administrator and Acting Administrator of the United States Maritime Administration since July 2009. He has more than a decade of experience in federal transportation policy and programs, previously serving as Deputy Assistant Secretary for Policy at the U.S. Department of Transportation. Matsuda has also worked in the United States Senate, helping to draft and pass important transportation legislation. He holds a B.S. in Engineering from Harvey Mudd College and a J.D. from the University of San Diego School of Law.

President Obama also announced his intent to nominate Michael P. Huerta as Deputy Administrator of the Federal Aviation Administration at the Department of Transportation. Huerta has his own consulting firm, advising clients on transportation policy, technology, and financing. He previously served as Group President of the Transportation Solutions Group of Affiliated Computer Services, Inc., and held senior positions at the Department of Transportation under President Bill Clinton. Huerta has a master's degree from the Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs at Princeton University and a bachelor's degree from the University of California at Riverside. He currently serves as Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Intelligent Transportation Society of America and was a member of President Obama's transition team for the U.S. Department of Transportation.